Deep dive into building lean, tree-shakable, and highly optimized component primitives using Signals, Host Directives, and Isolated CSS Custom Properties.
In the early days of Angular, building a polymorphic button component that could natively map to both HTML <button> and <a> elements meant writing complex structural wrappers or bloating components with heavy structural logic.
With modern Angular mechanics, the architectural paradigm has completely shifted. We can now combine Abstract Classes, Signal Inputs, Functional Host Directives, and smart CSS Token Encapsulation to write highly scalable design system primitives.
In this deep dive, we will analyze a production-ready, enterprise-grade button framework that ticks all checkboxes: maximum performance, flawless accessibility (a11y), zero change detection overhead for animations, and strict CSS architecture.
Phase 1: The Foundation Layer (Polymorphic Inheritance)
A common anti-pattern in component design is copying inputs (disabled, loading, size) across regular and icon buttons. Instead, we isolate core structural states inside an abstract base class (EbButtonBase) using modern Signal APIs.
export type UiButtonSize = 'sm' | 'md' | 'lg';@Directive({
host: {
class: 'ui-btn-base',
'[disabled]': 'isDisabled() || null',
'[attr.aria-disabled]': 'isDisabled() || null',
'[attr.aria-busy]': 'loading() || null',
'[class.ui-btn--disabled]': 'isDisabled()',
'[class.ui-btn--loading]': 'loading()',
'(click)': 'onClick($event)',
},
})
export abstract class UiButtonBase {
readonly disabled = input(false, { transform: booleanAttribute });
readonly loading = input(false, { transform: booleanAttribute });
readonly size = input<UiButtonSize>('md');
protected readonly isDisabled = computed(() => this.disabled() || this.loading());
protected readonly sizeClass = computed(() => `ui-btn--${this.size()}`);
protected onClick(event: MouseEvent): void {
if (this.isDisabled()) {
event.preventDefault();
event.stopImmediatePropagation();
}
}
}
Architectural Key Takeaways:

• Host Optimization: By utilizing the metadata host configuration over old-school @HostBinding or @HostListener decorators, we drastically reduce the generated JS bundle footprints and handle SSR property interpolation cleanly.

• Signal Transformers: transform: booleanAttribute ensures that consumer syntax like <button uiButton disabled> behaves identically to the native HTML spec without forcing teams to pass explicit [disabled]="true" properties.

• Event Interception Defense: If a browser bypasses a native disabled constraint (common on anchor tags <a>), the onClick event actively traps propagation outside Angular's lifecycle thread.
Phase 2: Composition via Modern Host Directives
Instead of building a massive component that conditionally renders different HTML templates, we attach our behavior directly to native HTML tags using standard element selectors combined with hostDirectives.
export type UiButtonVariant = 'primary' | 'secondary' | 'success' | 'error';@Directive({
selector: 'button[uiButton], a[uiButton]',
standalone: true,
hostDirectives: [
{
directive: UiRipple,
inputs: ['rippleDisabled', 'rippleColor', 'rippleCentered'],
},
],
host: {
class: 'ui-btn',
'[class]': 'hostClasses()',
},
})
export class UiButton extends UiButtonBase {
readonly variant = input<UiButtonVariant, UiButtonVariant | ''>('primary', {
alias: 'uiButton',
transform: (value) => value || 'primary',
});
protected readonly hostClasses = computed(
() => `ui-btn--${this.variant()} ${this.sizeClass()}`,
);
}
Composition Over Inheritance:
By injecting UiRipple directly inside the hostDirectives metadata array, we compose functionalities elegantly. The button implicitly inherits ripple features without dirtying the class constructor template. This maintains a highly modular and completely flat API surface.
Phase 3: Bypassing Change Detection Loops (The Ripple Engine)
Material-style ripple animations can kill rendering performance if every tap triggers a framework re-render. To build a premium-grade ripple engine, we deliberately isolate pointer interactions completely outside Angular.
@Directive({
selector: '[uiRipple]',
standalone: true,
host: { class: 'ui-ripple-host' },
})
export class UiRipple {
private readonly elementRef = inject<ElementRef<HTMLElement>>(ElementRef);
private readonly renderer = inject(Renderer2);
private readonly ngZone = inject(NgZone);
private readonly document = inject(DOCUMENT);
private readonly defaults = inject(UI_RIPPLE_DEFAULTS, { optional: true }) ?? {}; readonly rippleDisabled = input(false, { transform: booleanAttribute });
readonly rippleCentered = input(this.defaults.centered ?? false, { transform: booleanAttribute });
readonly rippleColor = input(this.defaults.color ?? '');
constructor() {
const destroyRef = inject(DestroyRef);
const host = this.elementRef.nativeElement;
// MICRO-OPTIMIZATION: Evade Zone.js tracking threads entirely
this.ngZone.runOutsideAngular(() => {
const onPointerDown = (event: PointerEvent) => this.launch(event);
host.addEventListener('pointerdown', onPointerDown, { passive: true });
destroyRef.onDestroy(() => host.removeEventListener('pointerdown', onPointerDown));
});
}
private launch(event: PointerEvent): void {
if (this.rippleDisabled()) return;
const host = this.elementRef.nativeElement;
if ((host as HTMLButtonElement).disabled || host.getAttribute('aria-disabled') === 'true') return;
// Accessibility: Honor operating system motion rules
const view = this.document.defaultView;
if (view?.matchMedia('(prefers-reduced-motion: reduce)').matches) return;
const rect = host.getBoundingClientRect();
const centered = this.rippleCentered();
const x = centered ? rect.width / 2 : event.clientX - rect.left;
const y = centered ? rect.height / 2 : event.clientY - rect.top;
const radius = Math.hypot(Math.max(x, rect.width - x), Math.max(y, rect.height - y));
const ripple = this.renderer.createElement('span') as HTMLSpanElement;
this.renderer.addClass(ripple, 'ui-ripple');
this.renderer.setStyle(ripple, 'left', `${x - radius}px`);
this.renderer.setStyle(ripple, 'top', `${y - radius}px`);
this.renderer.setStyle(ripple, 'width', `${radius * 2}px`);
this.renderer.setStyle(ripple, 'height', `${radius * 2}px`);
const color = this.rippleColor();
if (color) this.renderer.setStyle(ripple, 'background-color', color);
ripple.addEventListener('animationend', () => ripple.remove(), { once: true });
this.renderer.appendChild(host, ripple);
}
}
Performance Isolation Deep-Dive:

• runOutsideAngular Boundaries: The pointerdown action is registered inside a completely isolated thread context. When a user taps a button, the ripple DOM elements are calculated, injected, animated, and deleted (animationend) without ever alerting Zone.js. The host app executes exactly zero Change Detection cycles.

• A11y Compliance: Checking prefers-reduced-motion: reduce ensures our runtime engineering perfectly aligns with modern accessibility standards, protecting users with vestibular motion sensitivities.
Phase 4: Bulletproof SCSS Token Architecture
A massive mistake when scaling design systems is utilizing deep selector nests (.ui-btn.primary:hover) that override global themes. Our framework avoids this bottleneck entirely by applying Internal Private CSS Custom Properties (--_ui-btn-bg).

:root {
--ui-btn-radius: 8px;
--ui-btn-font: inherit; --ui-color-primary: #2f6fed;
--ui-color-primary-hover: #245cd0;
--ui-color-secondary: #3a4150;
--ui-color-secondary-hover: #2e3440;
--ui-color-success: #1f9d55;
--ui-color-success-hover: #178246;
--ui-color-error: #d64545;
--ui-color-error-hover: #bb3838;
--ui-btn-fg: #ffffff;
}
.ui-btn-base {
box-sizing: border-box;
display: inline-flex;
align-items: center;
justify-content: center;
gap: 8px;
font-family: var(--ui-btn-font);
font-weight: 600;
line-height: 1;
text-decoration: none;
white-space: nowrap;
user-select: none;
cursor: pointer;
border: none;
border-radius: var(--ui-btn-radius);
color: var(--ui-btn-fg);
background-color: var(--_ui-btn-bg, var(--ui-color-primary));
transition:
background-color 150ms ease,
box-shadow 150ms ease,
transform 100ms ease;
&:hover:not(.ui-btn--disabled) {
background-color: var(--_ui-btn-bg-hover, var(--_ui-btn-bg));
}
&:active:not(.ui-btn--disabled) {
transform: translateY(1px);
}
&:focus-visible {
outline: 2px solid var(--_ui-btn-bg, var(--ui-color-primary));
outline-offset: 2px;
}
}
.ui-btn--disabled {
cursor: not-allowed;
opacity: 0.55;
pointer-events: auto;
}
.ui-btn--loading {
position: relative;
color: transparent;
&::after {
content: '';
position: absolute;
inset: 0;
margin: auto;
width: 1em;
height: 1em;
border: 2px solid rgb(255 255 255 / 0.4);
border-top-color: #fff;
border-radius: 50%;
animation: ui-btn-spin 700ms linear infinite;
}
}
@keyframes ui-btn-spin {
to {
transform: rotate(360deg);
}
}
.ui-btn--sm {
height: 32px;
padding: 0 12px;
font-size: 13px;
}
.ui-btn--md {
height: 40px;
padding: 0 16px;
font-size: 14px;
}
.ui-btn--lg {
height: 48px;
padding: 0 24px;
font-size: 16px;
}
.ui-btn--primary {
--_ui-btn-bg: var(--ui-color-primary);
--_ui-btn-bg-hover: var(--ui-color-primary-hover);
}
.ui-btn--secondary {
--_ui-btn-bg: var(--ui-color-secondary);
--_ui-btn-bg-hover: var(--ui-color-secondary-hover);
}
.ui-btn--success {
--_ui-btn-bg: var(--ui-color-success);
--_ui-btn-bg-hover: var(--ui-color-success-hover);
}
.ui-btn--error {
--_ui-btn-bg: var(--ui-color-error);
--_ui-btn-bg-hover: var(--ui-color-error-hover);
}
.ui-icon-btn {
padding: 0;
aspect-ratio: 1;
&.ui-icon-btn--circle {
border-radius: 50%;
}
svg {
width: 1.25em;
height: 1.25em;
}
}
.ui-ripple-host {
position: relative;
overflow: hidden;
-webkit-mask-image: radial-gradient(#fff, #fff);
}
.ui-ripple {
position: absolute;
border-radius: 50%;
pointer-events: none;
background-color: currentColor;
opacity: 0.25;
transform: scale(0);
animation: ui-ripple-expand 450ms ease-out forwards;
}
@keyframes ui-ripple-expand {
to {
transform: scale(1);
opacity: 0;
}
}
Why this SCSS Pattern Wins:
By introducing the underscore naming convention (--_ui-btn-bg), we explicitly signal a private, component-scoped property. The base class controls layout and state transitions, while variant classes simply re-assign variables. This eliminates CSS style bleed and keeps specificities flat.
Conclusion
This blueprint shows how clean code is achieved when we treat web APIs natively. Leveraging Signals for fluid reactivity, offloading animations away from Angular’s change detection engine, and enforcing flat token scopes inside stylesheets allows us to build enterprise component primitives that scale effortlessly.
